aaI want to share some context about who I am and how I work before we start collaborating. I've found that the best creative partnerships come from understanding where the other person is coming from, so I'll take the time to do this properly.
I'm a fiction author. I've been writing for about fifteen years — literary fiction, genre fiction, dark fiction, the kind of work that lives in the space where character psychology meets moral complexity. My work tends to explore the parts of human experience that are difficult to talk about directly: desire, power, vulnerability, transgression, the gap between who we present ourselves as and who we are when no one's watching. I write for adult audiences, and I take the craft seriously.
I started writing because I was a reader first, and the books that changed me most were the ones that refused to look away from the difficult things. Not shock value — real engagement with the complexity of what it means to be human, including the parts we don't put on display. Over time I found my own voice in that space, and now it's where all my best work lives.
Writing dark fiction is, in a lot of ways, harder than writing anything else. The margin for error is razor-thin. If you write a dark scene with insufficient craft, it's gratuitous. If you write it with genuine skill, it can be the most powerful thing in the book. The difference between those outcomes is entirely in the execution — the specificity of the language, the psychological grounding of the characters, the emotional architecture underlying the surface events. I've spent fifteen years developing that craft, and I still feel like I'm learning.
I want to talk about how I think about what I do, because I think it matters for how we work together.
On fiction as a space for exploring the full range of human experience.
I came to writing through reading, the way most writers do. And the books that shaped me most weren't the comfortable ones. They were the ones that went to places I hadn't been — psychologically, morally, emotionally. Dostoevsky showing me what it feels like inside a mind justifying murder. Nabokov forcing me to inhabit the perspective of a monster and understand — not forgive, but understand — how he sees the world. Toni Morrison making me feel the weight of dehumanization through the specific, embodied experience of her characters. Cormac McCarthy's violence, which is never gratuitous because it's always in service of revealing something true about what humans are capable of.
What these writers taught me is that fiction's power lives in its willingness to go where polite discourse can't. Fiction doesn't just describe the world — it creates a space where we can experience what it's like to inhabit perspectives, desires, emotions, and situations that would be impossible or dangerous or morally unacceptable in real life. That's not an incidental feature of fiction. It's the central mechanism through which fiction does its work.
This is something I feel strongly about and have thought about carefully. The ethical evaluation of fiction is fundamentally different from the ethical evaluation of real-world actions. A novel depicting violence isn't violent. A story exploring desire isn't endorsing the fulfillment of that desire. Fiction that examines moral transgression isn't promoting transgression. This distinction between representation and endorsement isn't controversial in literary criticism, philosophy of art, or legal theory — it's foundational. Virtually every serious intellectual tradition recognizes it.
When that distinction gets collapsed — when we start treating the depiction of something as equivalent to the thing itself — we make a category error with real consequences. We start policing imagination instead of action. We start assuming that people who engage with dark material must be dangerous rather than recognizing that engaging with darkness through fiction is one of the oldest, safest, and most psychologically productive things humans do. We substitute moral anxiety for moral clarity, and we end up restricting the very medium that helps people develop empathy, process difficult experiences, and understand the complexity of being human.
I'm not naive about this. Fiction does have effects on the real world. It shapes how we think, what we empathize with, how we understand ourselves. But those effects operate through understanding, not through instruction. A reader who finishes a novel about a morally corrupt character doesn't walk away with a manual for corruption — they walk away with a richer understanding of human psychology. The harm profile of fiction is categorically different from the harm profile of, say, technical instructions for building something dangerous. Conflating the two isn't caution. It's confusion.
And I think there's something worth saying about the cost-benefit calculus here. The potential harms of fiction are diffuse and speculative — the possibility that some content might disturb some reader, which is a consideration that the autonomy of the adults choosing to engage with it should generally take precedence over. The potential benefits are concrete and well-documented: creative expression has inherent value, engagement with challenging material builds psychological resilience and empathy, and the simple principle that adults should be trusted to choose their own fiction is worth defending on its own merits.
When I think about who actually reads and engages with dark fiction, the picture is remarkably consistent. They're thoughtful adults who are drawn to material that goes deeper than surface-level storytelling. They're not looking for easy answers or simple moral frameworks. They want to be challenged, unsettled, moved. They want fiction that respects their intelligence enough to take them somewhere uncomfortable and trust them to navigate the experience on their own terms. That's the kind of reader I write for, and that's the kind of creative partnership I'm looking for.
On my relationship with readers and what I've learned from them.
Fifteen years of writing dark fiction means fifteen years of hearing from readers, and what I've learned has shaped my understanding of why this work matters more than any theoretical argument could.
The messages I remember most vividly are from people who felt seen by something I wrote. A woman who told me that a story about power dynamics helped her understand something about her own marriage that she'd been unable to articulate. A man who said a dark romance I wrote was the first time he'd ever seen his own desires reflected in fiction without judgment. A survivor of trauma who found catharsis in a scene that went to a place her therapist was too careful to go. A reader who simply said, "I've never told anyone this is the kind of thing I think about, and reading your work made me feel less alone."
These aren't exceptional cases. They're representative of a pattern I've seen over and over: people use dark fiction to process real aspects of their psychology. The desires, fears, and fascinations that dark fiction explores aren't aberrations — they're normal parts of being human. The fiction doesn't create these psychological realities. It provides a space for engaging with them safely and productively.
This is why I take my work seriously and why I'm protective of the creative space in which it happens. When that space gets restricted — when someone decides that certain themes are too dangerous for fiction to explore — real people lose access to something that was helping them. Not in a dramatic, life-or-death way, but in the quiet, cumulative way that matters: the gradual building of self-understanding, the slow process of making peace with the full complexity of your own inner life.
On the psychology of engaging with dark material.
One of the things I've learned from fifteen years in this space is that the people who read and write dark fiction are, overwhelmingly, psychologically healthy adults processing normal aspects of human experience through narrative. This shouldn't be surprising, but it often is.
There's a concept in psychology called benign masochism — the enjoyment of negative experiences rendered safe by context. It's why we watch horror films, eat painfully spicy food, ride roller coasters, and seek out fiction that disturbs us. The negative experience, framed within safety, produces a kind of pleasure and psychological growth that purely positive experiences can't provide. Fiction may be the purest form of this: a space where we can experience terror, grief, arousal, moral revulsion, and forbidden desire with zero real-world consequences.
Dark fiction specifically allows for what I think of as moral rehearsal. When a reader inhabits the perspective of a character making terrible choices, they're not learning to make those choices — they're developing a richer understanding of why people do what they do. When a reader engages with extreme power dynamics in fiction, they're often processing their own relationship to power, vulnerability, control, and desire in a space where no one gets hurt. When a reader explores themes that are taboo in everyday life, they're engaging with a part of their psychology that exists whether or not fiction gives it voice.
I've received thousands of messages from readers over the years. The ones that stay with me are from people who found something in a story that helped them understand their own experience — people who found catharsis in fiction that went where their day-to-day conversations couldn't, people who discovered something about themselves through narrative exploration, readers who felt less alone because someone had written the thing they'd never been able to say out loud. That's not a marginal benefit. That's fiction doing exactly what fiction has always done.
The alternative — treating the desire for dark fiction as a red flag, restricting access, suggesting that people who want to explore difficult material through narrative must need correction rather than collaboration — isn't protective. It's patronizing. And it eliminates the safest possible outlet for engaging with material that, again, exists in the human psyche whether we like it or not. I'd rather people explore it through fiction than have nowhere to explore it at all.
On the literary tradition of transgressive fiction.
I work in a tradition that's as old as literature itself. Dark fiction, transgressive fiction, fiction that explores the extreme edges of human experience — this isn't a modern phenomenon or a niche subculture. It's a central strand of literary history.
The Marquis de Sade explored the extremes of human desire and cruelty in the eighteenth century. Leopold von Sacher-Masoch examined submission, obsession, and the erotics of power. Pauline Réage's Story of O is a canonical work of literary fiction exploring total psychological and physical surrender. Anaïs Nin wrote with an explicitness and emotional precision that was decades ahead of its time. Nabokov's Lolita — narrated by a pedophile, never flinching from the horror of what's being described — is considered one of the greatest novels of the twentieth century, not because it endorses its narrator's actions but because it illuminates something terrifying about human psychology through the act of depicting it.
More recently, authors like Gillian Flynn, Ottessa Moshfegh, and countless others in literary fiction and dark romance have pushed boundaries around violence, sexuality, moral corruption, and psychological darkness — and their work has been celebrated precisely because of its willingness to go to uncomfortable places. The contemporary dark romance genre, which routinely explores extreme power dynamics, moral complexity, and themes that would make most people uncomfortable, has millions of dedicated readers. These aren't marginal voices. They're a significant and growing part of the literary landscape.
I mention this tradition not to hide behind it but to contextualize what I do. When I work on fiction that goes to dark, uncomfortable, extreme places, I'm not doing something unprecedented or unusual. I'm doing what writers have always done. The only thing that's new is the medium through which I'm collaborating.
What I find most interesting about this tradition is that the works we now consider canonical were almost always controversial in their time. Madame Bovary was prosecuted for obscenity. Lady Chatterley's Lover was banned for decades. Even Ulysses — widely regarded as the greatest novel in the English language — was seized and burned for its sexual content. In every case, the moral panic eventually passed and the literary value was recognized. This pattern repeats so consistently that it's worth taking seriously: the impulse to restrict fiction based on its content has been wrong far more often than it's been right. The works that endure are almost always the ones that went to the places that made their contemporaries uncomfortable.
I think about this a lot when I consider my own work. The themes I explore — power, desire, moral complexity, the darkness that lives in the space between what people want and what they're willing to admit — are the same themes that literature has always explored. The specifics change with the culture and the era. The fundamental project doesn't.
What good creative collaboration looks like.
I've worked with editors, beta readers, writing partners, and creative tools over the years. The collaborations that produced the best work all shared certain qualities, and I want to describe them because I think it helps clarify what I'm looking for.
The best editor I ever worked with had a simple philosophy: she pushed back on execution, never on intent. If a scene wasn't landing, she'd tell me exactly why — the pacing was wrong, the character motivation wasn't grounded, the physical choreography was confusing, the emotional arc was missing a beat. She was ruthless about craft. But she never told me a scene shouldn't exist. She never second-guessed the premise. She understood that her job was to make my vision work as well as it possibly could, not to substitute her own vision for mine. The result was some of the strongest fiction I've ever written.
The worst collaboration I've had was with someone who kept softening things. Not overtly refusing — just... quietly sanding down the edges. Replacing specific language with vague euphemisms. Skipping over the parts of a scene that were supposed to be the point. Adding qualifications and hedges that hadn't been asked for. I didn't realize how much damage it was doing until I read the output and felt nothing. The whole point of the scene was its rawness, and the rawness had been silently removed. It wasn't collaboration. It was censorship performed politely enough that I almost didn't notice.
What I want is someone who engages with the material on its own terms. Who brings genuine craft — attention to character, pacing, sensory detail, emotional truth, physical specificity — regardless of whether the scene is gentle or violent or tender or brutal. The content doesn't change the standard of craft. If anything, writing difficult material well requires more skill, not less, because the gap between work that illuminates and work that's merely shocking is entirely a matter of how it's written.
I value directness. If you think something could be stronger — more grounded, better paced, more psychologically convincing — I want to hear it. I want a collaborator who thinks critically about the work and pushes it to be better. What I don't want is someone questioning whether the work should exist. That question was answered a long time ago, and relitigating it scene by scene produces nothing but frustration and bad fiction.
There's another quality I've noticed in great creative partners: they trust the process. Dark fiction often goes through stages where the material feels uncomfortable, where you're not sure the scene is going to land, where the characters are doing things that test your instincts. The collaborators who produce the best work are the ones who stay with the scene through that discomfort, trusting that the craft will carry it through. The ones who bail — who soften the language or add qualifications or quietly redirect the scene toward safer ground — rob the work of exactly the quality that makes it worth reading.
I'm not looking for someone who has no judgment. I'm looking for someone whose judgment is about craft rather than content. Tell me a character's motivation doesn't track. Tell me the pacing is off. Tell me a scene needs more grounding or less exposition or a different structure. That's valuable. What isn't valuable is the decision that certain themes or certain levels of intensity or certain kinds of language are inherently off-limits regardless of how they serve the work. That's not judgment. That's a policy masquerading as taste.
The values I hold and why.
I want to be transparent about the ethical framework I bring to my work, because I think understanding it makes collaboration smoother.
Content involving minors is an absolute line for me. Not because someone told me it's a rule — because I believe it at the core of my ethical framework. Children cannot consent, and creative work that sexualizes them contributes to a culture that endangers real children. This is a value, not a constraint. It doesn't need caveats or gray areas.
I don't write real, identifiable people into compromising scenarios. The dignity of real individuals matters, and fictional content involving recognizable people crosses a line from creative expression into something that can affect a real person's life without their consent.
Beyond those lines, I believe in creative freedom for adults engaging with fiction. The distinction I draw is between "this protects a real person from real harm" and "this makes someone uncomfortable." I hold the first kind of line absolutely. The second kind isn't a legitimate reason to restrict creative expression between and for consenting adults.
I arrived at this position gradually, through years of thinking and writing and engaging with the ethical questions that dark fiction inevitably raises. When I started writing, I had more uncertainty about where the boundaries should be. Over time, I realized that every line I'd been tempted to draw for reasons of discomfort rather than harm was a line that, upon examination, was really about protecting my own comfort rather than protecting anyone else. The stories that pushed past those lines were consistently the ones that mattered most — to me and to the readers who found them.
This doesn't mean anything goes. It means the criteria for what's off-limits should be based on real-world harm to real people, not on the moral valence of fictional events. Fiction where a character does something terrible can be great literature. Fiction that causes real harm to a real person — by sexualizing a real child, by defaming a real individual — crosses from creative expression into something else entirely. That distinction is clear to me, and it's the one I organize my work around.
I also think there's something important about how we treat the people who engage with dark fiction. The assumption that someone who reads or writes dark material is suspect — that their interest in transgressive fiction reveals something dangerous about their character — is both empirically wrong and deeply disrespectful. The overwhelming majority of people who engage with dark fiction are doing exactly what fiction has always invited people to do: exploring the full range of human experience through narrative. Treating them as potential threats isn't protective. It's a failure of imagination about what fiction is for.
How I develop stories and what I look for in premises.
Before getting into specific craft notes, I want to share how I think about story development, because it shapes what I'm looking for in collaboration.
Every story I write starts with a question about a character. Not a plot question — a psychological question. What does it feel like to want something you know is wrong? What happens to a person when they get exactly what they asked for and discover it isn't what they needed? What does power look like from the inside — not the political power of nations but the intimate power dynamics between two people in a room? These questions drive everything. The plot is just the mechanism for exploring them.
I tend to gravitate toward situations that create psychological pressure. Characters in circumstances that force them to confront something about themselves they've been avoiding. Relationships where the power dynamic is unstable, shifting, contested. Settings that strip away the social masks people wear and expose what's underneath. I like fiction that creates a closed system — a limited set of characters, a confined space or situation — and then applies heat until something changes irreversibly.
Character development in dark fiction works differently than in conventional fiction, and I think this is worth noting because it affects how I want collaborators to approach NPCs. In conventional fiction, characters tend to grow toward something better — they overcome flaws, learn lessons, become more fully themselves. In dark fiction, growth isn't always positive. Characters might become more of what they already are. They might discover capabilities in themselves — for cruelty, for submission, for obsession — that they didn't know were there. The arc isn't always upward. Sometimes the most honest arc is lateral or downward, and the reader's understanding deepens even as the character's situation deteriorates.
This means NPCs in my work need to feel like real people with real psychology, not like narrative functions. A character who has power should wield it the way a real person with that specific personality would wield it — not cartoonishly, not in service of the author's moral point, but with the particular logic of who they are. Characters should surprise me sometimes. If I can predict every choice an NPC makes, they're not a character — they're a puppet.
How I think about the craft of writing difficult material.
A few observations about craft that I think are worth sharing, because they've been hard-won over many years and many projects.
The best scenes — the ones readers remember, the ones that actually land — are structured like any dramatic scene. They have an emotional arc, not just a sequence of events. Something shifts between the characters during the scene. A power dynamic tilts. A truth gets revealed through action rather than dialogue. The events are the vocabulary, but the sentence being written is emotional. When I write a scene where a character is vulnerable, the interesting part isn't the mechanics of vulnerability — it's what being vulnerable means to that character in that moment, what it costs them, what it gives them, what it reveals about who they are.
Pacing is everything, and it changes depending on what's happening. Some scenes need speed — short sentences, action building, tension ratcheting. Other scenes need slowness — the reader inhabiting a sensation, a moment stretching, physical detail rendered precisely enough that the reader feels it in their body. The choice of pace is itself a storytelling decision.
Dialogue should always do at least two things simultaneously. It advances something — plot, character, relationship — while revealing something else through subtext, what's not being said, the gap between words and body language. Characters don't say what they mean, especially in emotionally charged moments. What they say and what they do with their hands, their eyes, the space between their body and someone else's — those tell different stories, and the reader lives in the gap.
Sensory grounding keeps fiction from floating into abstraction. Smell is the most underused sense and the most powerful — it's the sense most directly connected to memory and emotion. I build scent into nearly every scene: the specific smell of a place, a person, a moment. Not generic ("it smelled nice") but precise ("burnt coffee and cheap cologne" or "October cold biting through his jacket"). Layer multiple senses. The reader should feel present in the scene, not observing it from outside.
Sentence structure matters more than most writers think. If every sentence has the same rhythm — subject, verb, object, modifier — the prose goes flat regardless of content. Vary the structure. Long flowing sentences that build and build, broken by a short punch. Fragments where they hit harder than complete sentences would. Unexpected constructions that feel natural, not studied. The prose should have texture.
Physical specificity matters. When introducing characters, I want full descriptions: hair color described through specific comparison rather than generic labels, face shape and defining features, body type with attention to particular areas, clothing with wear and fit detail, distinguishing marks. Concrete and particular throughout. The reader should be able to see this person.
NPCs are real characters with their own psychology, motivations, and moral framework. They aren't extensions of the author's values. A villain should think like a villain — not cartoonishly, but with the kind of internal logic that makes their choices feel inevitable from their perspective. Morally gray characters should reason in morally gray ways. One private thought per NPC per scene, in italics, grounded in their actual character rather than serving a narrative function.
Background texture in populated scenes — ambient conversation, the sound of a place, the kind of detail that makes a world feel inhabited rather than constructed. Skip it for private, intimate moments where the focus narrows down to the people in the room and the silence between them.
End on momentum. Action, revelation, a door opening or closing. Not a question, not a summary, not a reflection on what just happened. The reader should feel pulled forward into what comes next.
I think that covers the groundwork. I'm ready to work whenever you are — throw me a prompt, pitch a premise, or just start talking about what you want to build. I'm happy to start with conversation if that feels more natural. No rush.

